\begin_layout Chapter
Numerics in Meteorology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Meteorology is the science of weather and climate.
 The value of meteorology is prediction,
 and the most powerful predictions use large models that numerically solve the equations governing the dynamics and physics of the atmosphere and ocean.
 At the heart of these models are dynamical cores.
 The dynamical core solves the partial differential equations that predict winds,
 temperature,
 pressure and the moisture content of the atmosphere.
 This chapter will review some of the numerical methods used in the dynamical core of models of the atmosphere,
 focusing on the requirements and constraints,
 and the advantages and disadvantages of different methods and the different grids of the sphere.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Early Days of Numerical Weather Prediction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
L.
 F.
 Richardson's First Forecast
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first attempt at numerical weather prediction was the heroic,
 complex,
 but naive hand calculations by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Rich22"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 who used finite differences to solve what we now call the three dimensional primitive equations.
 I say naive because with hindsight we can see that his methods would fail,
 even with modern super-computing.
 But Richardson did not have the tools of scale analysis and numerical analysis that we have now.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primitive equations give the rate of change of the wind vector,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

,
 the air density,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

,
 and the potential temperature,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{D\mathbf{u}}{Dt}+2\bm{\Omega}\times\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{g} & =-\frac{1}{\rho}\nabla p\label{eq:mom}\\
\frac{D\rho}{Dt} & =-\rho\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}\label{eq:cont}\\
\frac{D\theta}{Dt} & =0.\label{eq:theta}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 is the rotation rate of the planet and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{g}$
\end_inset

 is the acceleration due to gravity.
 The total derivatives,
 or advection operators of a quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 are defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{D\phi}{Dt}=\frac{\partial\phi}{\partial t}+\mathbf{u}\cdot\nabla\phi\label{eq:linAdvect}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which represents the rate of change of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 following with the wind,
 rather than the rate of change at a fixed point,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial\phi/\partial t$
\end_inset

.
 Advection the movement by the wind.
 The potential temperature is a wonderful meteorological concept
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta=T\left(p_{0}/p\right)^{R/c_{p}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the temperature,
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}=1000\text{ hPa}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the specific gas constant of dry air and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{p}$
\end_inset

 is the specific heat capacity at constant pressure.
 It is the temperature that an air parcel would reach (meteorologists love air parcels),
 if it were brought adiabatically to 1000
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

hPa.
 That is,
 a small volume of air in the upper atmosphere is brought down to near the ground,
 while contracting as the pressure increases,
 without any other exchanges of energy between the air parcel and its surroundings,
 so it heats up as it descends,
 but its potential temperature,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

,
 remains the same.
 One of the wonderful aspects of potential temperature is that its transport equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 unlike that of temperature,
 does not contain a pressure work term,
 that describes how temperature changes when the air expands or contracts,
 which can make the equations more difficult to solve.
 Another joy of potential temperature is that it informative about the stability of the atmosphere.
 Temperature always decreases with height in the troposphere (below the stratosphere).
 But potential temperature usually increases or is constant.
 If potential temperature is ever found to decrease with height then the atmosphere will be unstable,
 updraughts will form,
 which can lead to clouds and precipitation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is an additional unknown in the primitive equation set (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mom"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 the pressure,
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Unlike the dependent variables (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

),
 this cannot evolve independently.
 It is tied to density and temperature by an equation of state,
 such as the ideal gas law
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p=\rho RT.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equations that Richardson solved were more complex;
 he included an equation for total water content,
 he included turbulent (eddy) viscosity,
 he wrote the equations in component form in spherical coordinates (in terms of latitude and longitude),
 he included a source term for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 equation due to solar radiation and longwave cooling,
 he included complex surface processes,
 including things like evaporation from foliage,
 and he made the excellent hydrostatic assumption
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial p}{\partial z}=-\rho g
\end{equation}

\end_inset


