\begin_layout Standard
Richardson was optimistic because he classified weather prediction as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

marching
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem (or hyperbolic),
 with information propagating from the initial conditions and from the boundaries,
 as opposed to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jury
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem,
 in which 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jurymen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sitting at the boundary must all agree simultaneously on then solution (elliptic).
 This classification was correct,
 but the information propagates so quickly,
 in the form of gravity waves,
 that we need to use numerical methods for solving elliptic problems (including simultaneous solutions in different locations) for solving the primitive equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Rich22"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 used centered finite differences,
 knowing them to give second-order accuracy (error are proportional to the square of the grid spacing,
 so as resolution increases,
 errors drop quadratically).
 He used a leapfrog method in time,
 which he described as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

step-over
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 To illustrate this method,
 we can consider the solution of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 equation in just one spatial dimension,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 which is the one-dimensional linear-advection equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}+u\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial x}=0.\label{eq:linAdvect1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If we store values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 on a grid in an array,
 indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{j}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 at position 
\begin_inset Formula $j\Delta x$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 is the grid spacing.
 Then we can make the second-order,
 centered approximation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial x}\bigg|_{j}=\frac{\theta_{j+1}-\theta_{j-1}}{2\Delta x}.\label{eq:CS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We also define 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 at time level 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 which is at time 
\begin_inset Formula $n\Delta t$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 is the time step.
 We can make a similar centered approximation for the rate of change:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}\bigg|^{(n)}=\frac{\theta^{(n+1)}-\theta^{(n-1)}}{2\Delta t}.\label{eq:CT}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CT"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) can be substituted into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linAdvect1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) to give an equation for the next time level based on old values:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{j}^{(n+1)}=\theta_{j}^{(n-1)}-\frac{u\Delta t}{\Delta x}\left(\theta_{j+1}^{(n)}-\theta_{j-1}^{(n)}\right).\label{eq:CTCSadvect}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is the explicit,
 centered in time,
 centered in space (CTCS) advection scheme (explicit meaning that the solution at the next time level is found from existing solutions).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Rich22"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 described a few alternatives for what to do at the very first time step,
 when you do not know values from two previous time levels,
 only one.
 This cost effective scheme is not used much as it generates solutions with oscillations.
 This is worth trying ...
\end_layout

