\begin_layout Standard
Solve the linear advection equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linAdvect1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) using the centered in time,
 centered in space scheme (CTCS,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CTCSadvect"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Use a periodic domain 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1)$
\end_inset

 of 40 points.
 Test the code using the initial conditions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta\left(x,0\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{2}\left(1-\cos\frac{2\pi\left(x-0.1\right)}{0.3}\right) & \text{for }x\in\left[0.1,0.4\right]\\
1 & \text{for }x\in\left[0.7,0.9\right]\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The Courant number is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c=\frac{u\Delta t}{\Delta x}.\label{eq:Courant}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Set the Courant number to be 0.4 and run for 10 time steps.
 You can compare with the analytic solution
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta\left(x,t\right)=\theta\left(x-ut,0\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Can you animate the solution?
 What can you say about the part of the solution that started from the smooth initial conditions?
 What do the discontinuities do to the solution?
 Why?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next try setting the Courant number to be 1.1 and animate the solution for 5 time steps.
 What is happening now?
 Why?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Insights Enabling Numerical Weather Prediction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jule 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Char48"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 explained why Richardson's forecast produced such wild results and,
 in doing so,
 was able to find the right simplification of the equations to make them tractable by numerical solution,
 with smooth solutions.
 Charney pointed out that aerodynamics had become tractable,
 in part by assuming that the air is close to incompressible,
 so the continuity equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cont"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is simplified:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}=0\implies\frac{D\rho}{Dt}=0.\label{eq:ico}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This simplification is not useful for weather prediction because density varies by orders of magnitude between the surface and the stratosphere.
 The primitive equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mom"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) include the representation of acoustic (sound) waves and gravity waves.
 Deep gravity waves,
 in which large regions of the atmosphere move up and down under the influence of gravity (like waves on the surface of the ocean) can propagate horizontally at similar speed to acoustic waves.
 If a numerical model for equations that represent these waves is explicit (solutions for the next time level are found from previous solutions) and if gradients are approximated using nearby grid point values,
 then time steps must be small to avoid unstable oscillations.
 To explore this,
 attempt the exercises in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:solveSW"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Example:
 Numerical Solution of Gravity Waves
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:solveSW"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primitive equations can be simplified and averaged in the vertical to produce the shallow-water equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{D\mathbf{u}}{Dt}+2\bm{\Omega}\times\mathbf{u} & =-g\nabla h\label{eq:SWu_vec}\\
\frac{Dh}{Dt} & =-h\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}\label{eq:SWh_vec}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the velocity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

,
 is only non-zero in the locally horizontal direction,
 ie perpendicular to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{g}$
\end_inset

.
 These equations work in this Cartesian form on the surface of the earth,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g=|\mathbf{g}|$
\end_inset

,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{g}$
\end_inset

 perpendicular to the local surface whereas 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Omega}=\mathbf{k}\Omega$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

 points up through the North pole.
 If we consider a local tangent plane to the sphere,
 then the shallow water equations can be written
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{Du}{Dt}-fv & =-g\frac{\partial h}{\partial x}\label{eq:SWu}\\
\frac{Dv}{Dt}+fu & =-g\frac{\partial h}{\partial y}\label{eq:SWv}\\
\frac{Dh}{Dt} & =-h\left(\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}+\frac{\partial v}{\partial y}\right)\label{eq:SWh}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(u,v\right)$
\end_inset

 are the velocity components in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 directions and the Coriolis parameter,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f=2\Omega\sin\phi$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the latitude.
 In order to represent only gravity waves,
 these equations are linearised by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $H+h$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is uniform in space and time and 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v,h$
\end_inset

 are assumed small.
 Just considering one spatial dimension and ignoring rotation (
\begin_inset Formula $f=0$
\end_inset

) gives a one-dimensional wave equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial u}{\partial t} & =-g\frac{\partial h}{\partial x}\label{eq:linSWu}\\
\frac{\partial h}{\partial t} & =-H\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}\label{eq:linSWh}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which has gravity wave speed 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{gH}$
\end_inset

.
 If the mean fluid depth,
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

,
 is,
 for example,
 the height of the troposphere,
 around 10
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

km,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\sim10\text{ m/s}$
\end_inset

 then the gravity wave speed is 316
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m/s,
 close to the speed of sound which is around 343
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

m/s.
 The linearised shallow water equations can be solved explicitly using finite differences on a staggered grid,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 stored at alternating locations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "an excellent choice made by"
key "Rich22"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{h_{j}^{(n+1)}-h_{j}^{(n)}}{\Delta t} & =-H\frac{u_{j+1/2}^{(n)}-u_{j-1/2}^{(n)}}{\Delta x}\label{eq:linSWh_FB_C}\\
\frac{u_{j+1/2}^{(n+1)}-u_{j+1/2}^{(n)}}{\Delta t} & =-g\frac{h_{j+1}^{(n+1)}-h_{j}^{(n+1)}}{\Delta x}\label{eq:linSWu_FB_C}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 is the time step and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the time level number so that 
\begin_inset Formula $t=n\Delta t$
\end_inset

 is the time.
 The values of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 are stored in arrays indexed by an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 The array for 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 at index 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 represents 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 at location 
\begin_inset Formula $j\Delta x$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 is the grid spacing.
 However the array for 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 at grid point 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 will actually represent 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 at location 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(j+1/2\right)\Delta x$
\end_inset

.
 Eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWh_FB_C"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) can be rearranged to give 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 at every grid point using a forward difference in time (the time derivative at time 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is approximated using time 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and the forward time,
 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

).
 Once we know 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

,
 this is used to update each 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j+1/2}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 using an explicit backward time difference.
 The resulting explicit time stepping scheme is called forward-backwards 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Mes77"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and it is stable provided the Courant number associated with gravity waves,
 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\sqrt{gH}\Delta t/\Delta x\le1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Rich22"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 used 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t=6\text{ hours}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x=200\text{ km}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

