\begin_layout Subsubsection
Solving Elliptic Equations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:ellipticSolutions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primitive equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mom"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 the linear advection equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linAdvect1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and the shallow-water equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWu_vec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWh_vec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) are hyperbolic,
 meaning that information propagates at a finite speed.
 This encouraged Richardson in developing an explicit time-stepping method.
 However,
 the propagation speeds are so fast that we actually need a numerical method similar to a numerical method for solving an elliptic equations.
 By making the incompressible approximation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ico"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) for the primitive equations,
 acoustic waves have infinite speed,
 making the problem elliptic.
 The incompressible approximation for the shallow-water equations can also be used to derive the barotropic vorticity equation.
 This is an equation for the vertical component of the total vorticity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

,
 which includes the vertical component of the relative vorticity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=\left(\nabla\times\mathbf{u}\right)\cdot\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset

,
 and planetary rotation (the Coriolis parameter,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta=\xi+f\label{eq:pv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Taking the curl of the momentum,
 applying some vector-calculus identities and assuming incompressiblity gives the barotropic voriticity equation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{D\eta}{Dt}=0\label{eq:baroVortEqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(see the mathematical exercises below).
 This seems wonderfully simple!
 The difficult bit comes is calculating the velocity from the vorticity by inverting (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pv"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) which is exactly the kind of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jurymen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem that Richardson wanted to avoid.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Char48"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 realised that some such elliptic solution was essential for avoiding severe time-step restrictions.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Char49"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 knew that weather forecasters relied mostly on charts of pressure to predict the weather.
 It should not be necessary to solve the full primitive equations,
 whose initialisation relies on accurate knowledge of winds,
 density and temperature.
 The wind is close to geostrophic balance
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{cccc}
u\approx-\frac{1}{\rho f}\frac{\partial p}{\partial y},\ \  & v\approx\frac{1}{\rho f}\frac{\partial p}{\partial x},\ \  & w\approx0 & \text{ or }\mathbf{u}=\mathbf{k}\times\frac{\nabla p}{\rho f}\end{array}\label{eq:geoBalance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so wind can be determined from the pressure (flowing anti-clockwise,
 or cyclonically,
 around low pressure in the Northern hemisphere).
 The winds advect (move) the pressure,
 making it evolve slowly,
 making the weather predictable.
 However geostrophic balance cannot be used to predict the weather.
 Geostrophic balance (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:geoBalance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) implies incompressibility and,
 substituting (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:geoBalance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) into the momentum equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mom"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) results in the wind and other variables never changing.
 This is a persistence forecast - the weather tomorrow will be the same as today.
 We don't need equations to make a persistence forecast.
 So it seems that we need need some way to ignore the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

entirely irrelevant gravity motions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "CFvN50"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 made the first numerical weather predictions by finding a pressure level in the atmosphere,
 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 where horizontal divergence is smallest.
 The equations are then formulated on this pressure surface,
 which has geopotential height,
 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "CFvN50"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 used 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}=500\text{ hPa}$
\end_inset

 and,
 to this day,
 much weather data is reported on the 
\begin_inset Formula $500\text{ hPa}$
\end_inset

 surface and ECMWF use the height of the 
\begin_inset Formula $500\text{ hPa}$
\end_inset

 surface,
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{500}$
\end_inset

,
 to verify their forecasts.
 Geostrophically balanced winds can be written in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{v}=-\frac{g}{f}\mathbf{k}\times\nabla z\label{eq:geoBalanceZ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is the horizontal component of the wind.
 Hence the two equations to be solved,
 for total vorticity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

,
 and geopotential height,
 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

,
 for the simplest weather prediction are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{D\eta}{Dt} & =0, & g\nabla\cdot\frac{1}{f}\nabla z & =\xi.\label{eq:baroVortGeoVort}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

