\begin_layout Subsubsection
Elliptic Solutions of Hyperbolic Equations – the semi-implicit method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ellipticSolutions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 described approximations of the hyperbolic primitive equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mom"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) by the elliptic vorticity equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:baroVortEqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The real atmosphere is,
 of course fully compressible,
 with finite speed acoustic and gravity waves and non-hydrostatic motions,
 so for the most accurate weather forecasts,
 all of these process need to be included,
 but without the time step being limited by the speed of the fastest waves.
 This is where semi-implicit time stepping comes in.
 The full equations are written as linearised equations that can be solved implicitly,
 and the non-linear and other slow parts are solved explicitly.
 Rather than describing semi-implicit time stepping for the primitive equations,
 we can consider the shallow-water equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWu_vec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWh_vec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and treat the fast,
 gravity waves implicitly and the advection and Coriolis terms explicitly.
 This description will be for a time-stepping scheme that is first-order accurate in time,
 but the same method can used with schemes that are higher-order accurate in time.
 Discretising in time only:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{DX}{DT}=\frac{\partial X}{\partial t}+\mathbf{u}\mathbf{\cdot}\nabla X\approx\frac{X^{(n+1)}-X^{(n)}}{\Delta t}+\mathbf{u}\mathbf{\cdot}\nabla X^{(n)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some dependent variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
 where the advection term,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}\mathbf{\cdot}\nabla X$
\end_inset

 is considered slow and so is treated explicitly,
 so the value at the old time level is used.
 So (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWu_vec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWh_vec"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) become
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\mathbf{u}^{(n+1)}-\mathbf{u}^{(n)}}{\Delta t}+\mathbf{u}^{(n)}\mathbf{\cdot}\nabla\mathbf{u}^{(n)}+2\bm{\Omega}\times\mathbf{u}^{(n)} & =-g\nabla h^{(n+1)}\label{eq:uSI}\\
\frac{h^{(n+1)}-h^{(n)}}{\Delta t}+\mathbf{u}^{(n)}\mathbf{\cdot}\nabla h^{(n)} & =-h^{(n)}\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}^{(n+1)}\label{eq:hSI}
\end{align}

\end_inset

with the terms involved in gravity-wave propagation (in the linearised equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) treated implicitly,
 using the new time level.
 Variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 both consist of arrays of values over a grid,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 is needed to update 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 is needed to update 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 To proceed,
 we split 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:uSI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) into its explicit and implicit parts and substitute this into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hSI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{u}^{(n+1)} & =\mathbf{u}^{\prime}-\Delta tg\nabla h^{(n+1)}\label{eq:backS}\\
\text{where }\mathbf{u}^{\prime} & =\mathbf{u}^{(n)}-\Delta t\left\{ \mathbf{u}^{(n)}\mathbf{\cdot}\nabla\mathbf{u}^{(n)}+2\bm{\Omega}\times\mathbf{u}^{(n)}\right\} \label{eq:uPrimeEqn}\\
\implies\frac{h^{(n+1)}-h^{(n)}}{\Delta t} & -\Delta tgh^{(n)}\nabla^{2}h^{(n+1)}=-\mathbf{u}^{(n)}\mathbf{\cdot}\nabla h^{(n)}-h^{(n)}\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}^{\prime}.\label{eq:hEqn}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The first step is to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 explicitly from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:uPrimeEqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hEqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) appears to be an elliptic equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and is sometimes called the pressure equation or a Helmholtz equation.
 All of the unknown values of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 can be put into an array.
 The discretisation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}h$
\end_inset

 can be represented as a matrix multiplied by this array.
 Then this matrix equation can be solved to find the array of all of the 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 values.
 The final step is the back-substitution,
 to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and the new values of 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{(n+1)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Exercise
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will assume a one-dimensional staggered grid (eqns 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 without rotation.
 So the continuous equations are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}+u\frac{\partial u}{\partial x} & =-g\frac{\partial h}{\partial x}\\
\frac{\partial h}{\partial t}+u\frac{\partial h}{\partial x} & =-h\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Write the semi-implicit method,
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hEqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) for this one-dimensional system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We will also assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $u>0$
\end_inset

 everywhere,
 for all time.
 This allows us to use a stable upwind approximation for the advection terms.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 can be calculated as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{j+1/2}^{\prime}=u_{j+1/2}^{(n)}-\Delta t\ u_{j+1/2}^{(n)}\frac{u_{j+1/2}^{(n)}-u_{j-1/2}^{(n)}}{\Delta x}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In exercise 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Ex_CTCSadvection"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we used a centered in space approximation for advection,
 which lead to oscillations in the solution.
 This upwind approximation,
 with information for calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial u/\partial x$
\end_inset

 coming only from upwind,
 leads to smooth solutions but it is less accurate.
 Using the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j}=\frac{1}{2}\left(u_{j-1/2}+u_{j+1/2}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 write down the upwind approximation for the term 
\begin_inset Formula $u\frac{\partial h}{\partial x}$
\end_inset

 at location 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
