\begin_layout Section
A Golden Era of Numerical Weather Prediction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Through the 1950s and 1960s,
 simulations of the atmosphere became more realistic and the models became more and more similar to those that are used now.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Smag58"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 solved the the primitive equations in three dimensions (with just two vertical levels).
 But the paper mostly discusses causes of instability and no plots of numerical results are presented,
 suggesting that there was little realism in the results.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Phil59"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 simulated the entire northern hemisphere with one horizontal layer,
 with a 24 hour simulation taking 84 minutes.
 Like 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Rich22"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Phil59"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was still blaming grid-scale oscillations on the lack of smoothness in the initial conditions rather than on the numerical methods.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Smag63"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 created a two-layer model between the equator and 64
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

N which he was able to run for 60 days,
 simulating baroclinic instability,
 poleward heat transport and a Hadley circulation,
 with some realism.
 Grid-scale oscillations were controlled using eddy viscosity to mimic the effects of turbulent diffusion.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Smag63"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 mentioned Arakawa's emerging work on energy conserving methods which would prove revolutionary in atmosphere and ocean modelling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Three Dimensional Solutions on Mainframe Computers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Arakawa's Numerics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:ArakawaGrids"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AL77"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 described the numerical methods used on the UCLA general circulation model;
 a landmark in the development of stable and accurate numerical methods for the atmosphere,
 a 92 page article that is still being cited (3,538 citations in total,
 with over 100 citations every year since 2014).
 The model is three dimensional with 12 vertical levels,
 
\begin_inset Formula $72\times45$
\end_inset

 grid points in the horizontal and a time step of 6 minutes.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AL77"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is best known for the description of the Arakawa grids - 5 arrangements of prognostic variables on a grid,
 labelled A-E.
 They wrote the momentum equation,
 for the horizontal velocity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

,
 in vector-invariant form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{D\mathbf{v}}{Dt}+f\mathbf{k}\times\mathbf{v}+\frac{1}{\rho}\nabla_{h}p+\nabla_{h}K=\mathbf{F}_{h}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\frac{1}{2}|\mathbf{v}|^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the kinetic energy,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}_{h}$
\end_inset

 is the horizontal component of the frictional force and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{h}$
\end_inset

 is the horizontal component of the gradient.
 Use of the vector-invariant form enables exact energy conservation,
 with losses in gravitiational potential being exactly transferred to kinetic energy,
 and back.
 The Arakawa grids A-E are shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Arakawa-A-E"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 The advantages and dis-advantages of these grids can best be seen in terms of the linearised shallow water equations.
 The one-dimensional linearised shallow water equations without Coriolis are (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The two-dimensioal linearised shallow water equations can be obtained by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $D/Dt$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial t$
\end_inset

 in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 with the constant,
 uniform average height,
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

,
 on the right hand side of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 As was investigated in example 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:solveSW"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 if all variables are located together,
 as in the A-grid,
 then the pressure (or height) gradients needed to update the velocity are calculated over three grid points,
 missing the central location (eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWu_FB_A"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) and the divergence needed to update the height in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) is calculated over three points in each direction,
 missing the central location (eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linSWh_FB_A"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 This omission of the central location means that grid-scale oscillations can develop – oscillations in 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 can be present which do not lead to height gradients,
 and oscillations in 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 can be present which do not lead to divergence.
 These oscillations are spurious computational modes and make the A-grid problematic for atmospheric modelling.
 Considering the height gradients and the divergence terms of eqns (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWu"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SWh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 the C-grid appears to be ideal – compact height gradients in the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-direction (using two points without missing out a central point),
 are centered at the 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 location,
 compact height gradients in the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

-direction are at the 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 location and the divergence can be calculated at the 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 location without missing any velocities at 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 This means that gravity wave propagation is most accurate and free of computational modes on the C-grid,
 and this grid was chosen by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AL77"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for the UCLA model.
 
\end_layout

