\begin_layout Subsubsection
Finite Volume A- and C-grids for unstructured meshes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:FV"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:FFSL"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 described finite volume methods for solving the linear advection equation,
 which has one dependent variable,
 which is stored as a volume average in each cell.
 Once we have multiple variables that create waves and,
 in particular,
 we are solving the momentum equation for the velocity components,
 we must return to Arakawa's problem of where to store different variables (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ArakawaGrids"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 This has added complexity because a finite volume mesh can include cells of arbitrary shapes,
 such as the triangles,
 pentagons and hexagons in icosahedral meshes (fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:grids"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purest form of finite volume is co-located,
 of A-grid,
 so that the velocity is stored as volume averages in the cells,
 the same as the variables that are advected by the wind.
 This approach is used effectively by NICAM 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SMT+08"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which stores all variables apart from vertical velocity in cells.
 Vertical velocity is stored at the top and bottom faces of cells.
 So NICAM uses the A-grid in the horizontal and the C-grid (staggered) in the vertical.
 ECMWF's finite volume model,
 PMAP,
 or FVM,
 currently a research model,
 is fully co-located with all variable stored in cells 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "KDK+19"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and is close to ECMWF's spectral transform model in terms of accuracy and efficiency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite excellent solutions from co-located (A-grid) finite volume models on various grids,
 the A-grid is always prone to grid-scale oscillations,
 which can usually be smoothed out with some kind of diffusion or filter.
 This has motivated the development of C-grid discretisations on triangles for the ICON model 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bon04,ZRR+15"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and on hexagons and pentagons for,
 example,
 MPAS 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "TRSK09,SKD+12,RPH+13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 ICON produces skilful global weather forecasts,
 but the underlying dynamical core is still prone to grid-scale oscillations and requires diffusion.
 It turns out that the C-grid on triangles is not as well behaved as hoped.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gas11"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 explained that the oscillations on triangles cannot be controlled by the insufficient normal velocity components at the triangle edges,
 and that the hexagonal C-grid performs better.
 MPAS,
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Model for Prediction Across Scales
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 was developed as a global version of the popular WRF model and uses the hexagonal C-grid 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SKD+12"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It is free of grid-scale oscillations in height or pressure,
 but spurious grid-scale circulations can appear around the hexagon vertices,
 a manifestation of the Hollingsworth instability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gas13"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finite-volume methods for wave equations (such as the A- and C-grid finite voulme methods),
 tend to be low-order accurate – usually up to second-order.
 However,
 despite the smooth,
 well behaved solutions,
 the C-grid on the hexagonal-icosahedron is found to be much less than second-order,
 with a complete loss of convergence with resolution in some situations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "YWM+20"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 who found serious deficiencies in both the A- and C-grids on hexagonal icosahedral meshes.
 This provides a strong motivation to move to more complex numerical methods on quasi-uniform meshes.
\end_layout

